{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f20593f7-2956-429e-bcd6-3faaa566c557","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Deep Import Chain (level1 → level2 → level3)\n\nThe project imports `level1.props`, which imports `level2.props`, which imports `level3.props`. Each nested import requires MSBuild to open, parse, and evaluate another XML file during the **evaluation phase**. Deep chains increase disk I/O and XML parsing overhead linearly with depth.\n\n## 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern\n\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n\nThe `**\\*.*` glob recursively scans the entire directory tree. It only excludes `bin` and `obj`, meaning it will still enumerate directories like `.git`, `node_modules`, or any other large folder. This forces MSBuild's evaluation engine to stat potentially thousands of files. **Fix:** restrict the glob to specific extensions/folders or add `DefaultItemExcludes` entries for known heavy directories.\n\n## 3. File I/O via Property Function During Evaluation\n\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n\nThis uses an MSBuild property function to perform synchronous file I/O **during evaluation**, not during task execution. Evaluation is supposed to be fast (property/item resolution only). Reading file contents here blocks the evaluator and cannot be parallelized or deferred. The content should instead be read during the execution phase (e.g., via a `ReadLinesFromFile` task in a target).\n\n## Summary\n\n| Issue | Impact |\n|-------|--------|\n| 3-level nested imports | Extra file opens + XML parses per evaluation |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Full recursive directory enumeration |\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | Synchronous disk I/O blocking evaluation |\n\n**Key concept:** MSBuild's *evaluation phase* resolves properties, items, and imports to build the in-memory project model. It runs before any targets execute. Expensive operations (broad globs, file reads, deep import trees) here cannot be skipped or deferred, making them disproportionately costly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cb4145f8-8095-4db8-86eb-9560bb357726","outputTokens":519,"requestId":"7C16:30C599:BF8CD6:DB70B5:6A027FC1"},"id":"5002a481-6e99-45ed-8b94-7d55c2df79ce","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:18:07.044Z","parentId":"548fc17f-a3f4-42b5-bc55-de770d6bbb83"}
